{"Title": "Citizen participation and changing governance: Cases of devolution in England", "Year": 2017, "Source": "Policy Polit.", "Volume": "45", "Issue": 2, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": 251, "PageEnd": 269, "CitedBy": 11, "DOI": "10.1332/030557317X14895974141213", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85018755722&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 Policy Press 2017.The current process of devolving powers within England constitutes a significant change of governance arrangements. This process of devolution has been widely criticised for including insufficient consultation. This paper assesses whether that criticism is fair. Modifying Archon Fung's framework for the analysis of public participation mechanisms, we begin by considering whether the depth of public engagement has been limited. Then, by comparing these consultation practices with other examples (including one we have ourselves trialled in pilot experiments), we find that deeper forms of public engagement would have been both possible (though at some financial cost) and productive.", "AuthorKeywords": ["Consultation", "Devolution", "Governance", "Public participation"], "IndexKeywords": null, "DocumentType": "Journal", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 2, "EID": "2-s2.0-85018755722", "SubjectAreas": [["Sociology and Political Science", "SOCI", "3312"], ["Public Administration", "SOCI", "3321"], ["Management, Monitoring, Policy and Law", "ENVI", "2308"]], "AuthorData": {"6603913569": {"Name": "Prosser B.", "AuthorID": "6603913569", "AffiliationID": "60008950", "AffiliationName": "Australian National University"}, "6602814584": {"Name": "Flinders M.", "AuthorID": "6602814584", "AffiliationID": "60001881", "AffiliationName": "University of Sheffield"}, "57201726743": {"Name": "Renwick A.", "AuthorID": "57201726743", "AffiliationID": "60022148", "AffiliationName": "University College London"}, "55701751100": {"Name": "Giovannini A.", "AuthorID": "55701751100", "Affil